# **Limitation Periods (Brief):** 

Generally, one has 6 years to bring a tort claim under s 6 of the Limitation Act (Cap 163\) but this position is modified by s 24A.

 If the tort claim involves damages in respect of personal injuries, you may only have 3 years. But the clock might not start until the victim has the required knowledge to bring the claim

# **Intentional Torts (Trespass to the Person):** 

## 

## **Battery**

1. ### **Is the defendant liable for the tort of battery for \[act\] on the plaintiff?**

* *Amutha Valli d/o Krishnan v Titular Superior of the Redemptorist Fathers in Singapore*: battery refers to the “actual infliction of unlawful force on another person”. Following The Law of Torts in Singapore, the elements of the tort of battery are as follows:  
1) Direct physical contact with the plaintiff.  
2) Intentional physical contact with the plaintiff; and  
3) Unjustified physical contact

## 

1) **Was there direct physical contact with the plaintiff?**  
* (Third party interference) *Scott v Shepherd*: the court held that the chain of directness will not be broken when there is third party interference. As the causal chain is not broken, the physical contact can be said to be effected directly by the \<Defendant\>.   
* (If defending the intermediate act) *Scott v Shepherd:* intermediate acts will not purge the original tort in the defendant. But he who does the first wrong is answerable for all the consequential damages...  
* (Use of instruments) *Amutha Valli d/o Krishnan* battery is the actual infliction of unlawful force on another person. In this regard, instruments could be used to effect the physical contact.  
* (No skin to skin contact) *Kaye v Robertson*: the court, albeit an obiter, the deliberate taking of flashlight photography of someone might amount to direct physical contact. As long as the ultimate contact effected is an extension of the defendant’s body, this factor will be made out.

2) **Intentional physical contact with the plaintiff**  
* *Note: Intention to make physical contact is sufficient, no need to intend harm, infer from facts of the case.*   
* (Continuance of an act) Intentional physical contact can arise from the continuance of an act:  
  * *Fagan v Commissioner of Metropolitan Police:* the defendant’s initial act in mounting the police officer’s foot with his car was considered unintentional. However, his subsequent deliberate delay or omission to move his car after he was made aware of the car’s position despite repeated shouts was inferred as an intentional act.  
* (No need for intent to injure) For the tort of battery, only an intention to commit the act of direct physical contact is needed as it is the mere trespass by itself which is the offence.

3) **Unjustified physical contact**  
* *Collins v Wilcock*: the test of justified physical contact are those “generally acceptable in the ordinary conduct of daily life”.   
* Similarly / Conversely, \<Defendant\>’s act of \<insert act of physical contact\> with the \<Plaintiff\> is likely acceptable / unacceptable in the ordinary conduct of life as \<justify with reasons\>.

2. ### **Conclusion**

* (+) Since all three elements of the tort of battery are fulfilled, and \<Defendant\> could not successfully raise any defences, \<Plaintiff\> will likely succeed in his claim against \<Defendant\> for the tort of battery.  
* (-) Since \<Defendant\> is likely successful in evoking the defence of \<defence\>, he will be absolved of his liability of battery. \<Plaintiff\> will not receive any damages.

## **False Imprisonment**

1. ### **Is the defendant liable for the tort of false imprisonment for \[act\] on the plaintiff?**

* \[Defendant\] may be liable for falsely imprisoning \[plaintiff\]. Following *Goel Adesh Kumar v Resorts World Sentosa*, for \[plaintiff\] to make out a case in the tort of false imprisonment, he must prove that:  
1) Defendant’s act caused the plaintiff to be confined within a particular area delimited by the defendant  
2) Defendant’s act directly resulted in P’s imprisonment;   
3) Confinement was intentional (ill-will not required);

1) **Defendant confined/ restrained P within delimited area**

	*Note: The first question must be whether the plaintiff had been “imprisoned” at all*

* (General) Following *Bird v Jones*, the confinement of \[plaintiff\] must have been total. Partial confinement would be insufficient to make out a case of false imprisonment. In Bird, the defendant merely blocked the path of the plaintiff, who was able to return from the way he came. Hence, there is a reasonably accessible escape route. The court held that this was insufficient to amount to confinement to a delimited area.  
* In the present case, \[plaintiff\] was clearly/clearly not confined to a delimited area as \[state facts\]. Therefore, this requirement is likely/likely not made out.

| Electronic tagging/ Non-physical imprisonment(?) | Following R (Jalloh) v Sec of State, electronic tagging can amount to falsely imprisoning someone because your movements will be tracked and was victim was warned that by breaking the curfew he who would be fined or face imprisonment which this would deprive him of his personal autonomy for coming and going as he pleases. |
| :---- | :---- |

2) **Defendant’s act was direct**  
* Following *Iqbal v Prison Officers Association*, \<guilty party\>’s act must directly and immediately result in the plaintiff’s imprisonment or confinement.   
* (+) Presently, there is no issue of directness as \[the defendant\] caused the imprisonment of \[the plaintiff\] as \[reasons\].

* (-) \[Caused by someone else\] Following *Davidson v Chief Constable*: The act of the defendant must be the direct and immediate cause of the plaintiff’s imprisonment. The court held that the defendant did not cause the plaintiff’s false imprisonment. In this case, the defendant provided information to police officers that the plaintiffs stole items from the store. The officers subsequently arrested the plaintiffs. As the officers were exercising their own discretion, the defendant did not directly cause the confinement  
* \[Similarly/Contrastingly\] to the facts of the case, there \[were/were no\] intervening factors between \<guilty party\>’s act. These factors are \_\_\_\_\_. Therefore, \<guilty party\> \[did/did not\] directly cause \<innocent party\>’s confinement

3) **Confinement/imprisonment was intentional**  
* \<innocent party\> must prove that \<guilty party\> intended to cause \<innocent party\>’s confinement. An intention to merely commit the act, without any awareness of the consequences would not be sufficient to satisfy the requirement. Additionally, foreseeability is not sufficient to establish intention as held in Iqbal. There must be intention to do the act (e.g. locking the door) and to cause the confinement (know that someone is inside the room).  
* Intention will be inferred from the factual matrix. Currently, there is \[no\] intention to confine \<innocent party\> as \_\_\_\_\_\_ (guilty party attempting to block, and deny innocent party leave...)

4) **Lawfulness (Defence?)**  
* Following *Goel Adesh Kumar v RWS*, the defendants were found liable for falsely imprisoning a plaintiff who had gotten into an argument with another person at a casino. The court held that the defendants had neither any lawful reason nor authority to detain the plaintiff.  
* In the present case, it is submitted that \[defendant\] did/did not have a lawful basis to detain \[plaintiff\] because \[reasons e.g. committed an unbailable crime/murder/rape/cheating in casino\].

# **Defences to Trespass:**

1. ### **Consent:**

* Must be voluntary, unequivocal, and informed  
* Can be withdrawn


2. ### **Necessity (to protect human life):**

* Usually a fiction invented for medical cases  
* Re A (conjoined twins)  
* In re F (mental incapacity)

3. ### **Self-defence**

* Must also be reasonable: Ashley v Chief Constable
